2026-04-16 12:12:27 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module relay contacts', 'ambient sensor module series path feeding switched output'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the PSU delivers a steady ~12 V, and the control module input is at ~11.99 V. However, the relay load-side node—the point that should be directly connected to the input when the relay is closed—is only at ~0.36 V, matching the low voltage observed at the output terminals. This indicates the majority of the supply voltage is being dropped across the relay or an internal series element in the control module, even when the relay is intended to be closed.\n\nSweeping both timing and sensitivity potentiometers through their full ranges had no effect on the 20‑s cycling or on the low voltage seen at the load, making misadjusted control settings unlikely. The ambient light sensor logic may still be functioning, but the actual power path through the relay or its series trace/connection has become high‑resistance or intermittently open. This produces a large voltage drop and prevents proper voltage from reaching the load, causing the lamp to turn off briefly as the failing contact changes state.\n\nTherefore, the root cause is almost certainly a faulty/high‑resistance relay contact or closely associated series conductor inside the ambient sensor (control) module. Replacing/repairing the relay and any series connection in the switched output path should restore a solid 12 V to the load and eliminate the periodic dropouts.'
